{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1dbfe89e-9fb5-4f4d-b824-5ff84032fcee","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet-trace collect \\\n  -p <PID> \\\n  --profile cpu-sampling \\\n  --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope trace.nettrace`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the [single-file standalone build](https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace) instead.\n- For production, `cpu-sampling` is low-overhead (~5%). Avoid `gc-verbose` under load.\n- If you need OS-level context (native frames, kernel), use **`dotnet-counters`** first to confirm CPU is managed, then fall back to `perf record` if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2a736697-3f90-4198-ab09-a0032babb0a4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question - I don't need to search any codebase, just provide expert advice.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"C3D6:1BD126:1BFC760:1FA2369:6A07C33F"},"id":"4f9e0a72-2688-4ce4-b33d-c2fca01cd533","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:07:22.832Z","parentId":"54b3e444-7cad-484f-8c7f-cf226e200a82"}
